The crude HTML filtering selections are just UI controls that produce a filter state. That is exactly what Streamlit is good at, and your current app architecture is already set up for it. You could extend the existing page/row model to capture those visualization options natively, with the same export/state pattern already in place. No reason to keep the HTML page for this part.

---

### Part 2: The Cesium viewer — cannot be replaced, but can be embedded

Cesium is a WebGL JavaScript library. It must run in a browser JS context. Streamlit cannot replicate that natively. However, you have a clean option: `st.components.v1.html()` or `st.components.v1.iframe()` can embed the Cesium viewer directly inside your Streamlit app. This means the user never leaves the Streamlit interface — the viewer appears inline, inside the app, triggered by a button click just like the old "go" button.

